-- Japanese Stock Futures Little Changed on U.S. Jobs, Europe Debt
-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 2012-01-05T23:36:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-05/japanese-stock-futures-little-changed-on-u-s-jobs-europe-debt-concerns.html
Japanese  stock (MXAP)   futures (TPX)  were little
changed as a pickup in U.S. employment buoyed investor
confidence, while higher borrowing costs in a French bond
auction added to concern Europe’s debt crisis is deepening.
Australian stocks dropped after prices for oil and metals fell.  American depositary receipts of  Honda Motor Co. (7267) , a carmaker
that gets more than 40 percent revenue in the U.S., rose 0.2
percent from the last close in  Tokyo . Those of  Mitsubishi UFJ
Financial Group Inc. (8306) , Japan’s biggest lender by market value,
fell 1 percent. BHP Billiton Ltd., Australia’s No. 1 oil
producer and the world’s biggest mining company by market value,
fell 0.5 percent.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 Stock Average (NKY)  expiring in
March closed at 8,490 in Chicago yesterday, compared with 8,500
in Osaka, Japan. The contracts were bid in the pre-market at
8,480 in Osaka at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index slipped 0.2 percent percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50
Index lost 0.7 percent in Wellington.  “We’re likely to see a tug of war in the market between
the bad news in Europe and the good news of improving data in
the  U.S. economy ,” said Juichi Wako, a senior strategist at
Tokyo-based Nomura Holdings Inc.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index (SPXL1)  fell 0.1 percent
today. The gauge rose 0.3 percent yesterday in  New York  as
improving jobs data offset reduced profit forecasts at companies
including Target Corp. and J.C. Penney Co.  French Debt  Stock futures reversed an early slump after ADP Employer
Services said payrolls increased by 325,000 last month, topping
the median forecast of economists for growth of 178,000 jobs.
Applications for  jobless benefits (INJCJC)  decreased to 372,000 in the
week ended Dec. 31, Labor Department figures showed. The median
estimate of 38 economists in a Bloomberg News survey was for
375,000 claims.  In  Europe , France sold 7.96 billion euros ($10.2 billion)
of debt, with borrowing costs rising in its first bond auction
of the year, as credit companies threaten to cut the nation’s
AAA rating.  The euro fell to an 11-year low against the yen and the
weakest level in 15 months versus the dollar on concern Europe’s
debt crisis is worsening. The 17-nation currency reached 98.48
yen last night, its lowest level since December 2000. Still, the
dollar rose to as high as 77.25 yen today in Tokyo from 76.73 at
the close of  stock trading  yesterday.  Higher borrowing costs in France sparked a drop in  oil
prices . Crude oil for February delivery lost 1.4 percent to
$101.81 a barrel yesterday in New York, its first drop in three
days. The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six metals
including copper and aluminum slid 0.5 percent.  The Bloomberg  China-US 55 Index (CH55BN)  of the most-actively traded
Chinese equities gained 2.3 percent to 99.96 yesterday.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index (MXAP)  declined 17 percent last year.
The  S&P 500  broke even and the Stoxx Europe 600 Index dropped 11
percent.  To contact the reporters on this story:
